{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"9d9a2bee-986b-4db0-980b-7e779c726bdd","content":"Here's what you need. For NativeAOT, `createdump` isn't bundled with the runtime, so you must point to it explicitly via `DOTNET_DbgCreatedumpPath`.\n\n**Pod spec changes:**\n\n```yaml\nspec:\n  containers:\n  - name: your-app\n    env:\n    # Enable automatic crash dump on unhandled exception / crash\n    - name: DOTNET_DbgEnableMiniDump\n      value: \"1\"\n    # Dump type: 1=Mini, 2=Heap, 3=Triage, 4=Full\n    - name: DOTNET_DbgMiniDumpType\n      value: \"4\"\n    # Path to createdump (required for NativeAOT — not bundled in runtime)\n    - name: DOTNET_DbgCreatedumpPath\n      value: \"/opt/tools/createdump\"\n    # Dump output path (%d = PID, %t = timestamp)\n    - name: DOTNET_DbgMiniDumpName\n      value: \"/tmp/dumps/coredump.%d.%t\"\n    volumeMounts:\n    - name: crash-dumps\n      mountPath: /tmp/dumps\n  volumes:\n  # Use a PersistentVolumeClaim instead if you need dumps to survive pod restarts\n  - name: crash-dumps\n    emptyDir:\n      sizeLimit: 2Gi\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n\n- **`DOTNET_DbgCreatedumpPath`** — critical for NativeAOT since there's no bundled `createdump`.\n- **`MiniDumpType=4`** (Full) gives the most detail; use `2` (Heap) for smaller dumps that still include managed heap data.\n- **`emptyDir`** is fine for collection by a sidecar or node agent, but swap to a **PVC** if dumps must survive pod eviction.\n- Ensure the `createdump` binary has execute permission and the container user can write to `/tmp/dumps`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"f6a3d3e3-9d83-400c-b0d1-e104db14e501","outputTokens":491,"requestId":"502C:3738F9:27A9B7:314F76:69F55483"},"id":"10efaffc-6da8-4987-a9eb-13728a87e805","timestamp":"2026-05-02T01:34:09.417Z","parentId":"65f41140-26de-49a1-917f-eae4ac9ac8a3"}
